{
  "doc_id": "2390",
  "text": "A prevailing hypothesis is that when a tumor outgrows its blood supply, the resulting hypoxia switches on hypoxia inducible factor (HIF) a signaling that stimulates the production of several pro-angiogenic factors [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . An important pro-angiogenic pathway is that mediated by the VEGF family of ligands, which includes six growth factors [VEGF-A, VEGF-B, VEGF-C, VEGF-D, VEGF-E, and placental growth factor (PlGF)] and three VEGF receptors [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The VEGFRs are transmembrane tyrosine kinases present mainly in endothelial cells. When circulating VEGFs bind to VEGFRs, signal transduction pathways are activated that may promote endothelial cell proliferation, differentiation, migration, and angiogenesis [CITATION_6] . The VEGF/ VEGFR signaling pathway is involved in normal developmental and wound healing processes such as embryologic development, skeletal growth, and wound healing [CITATION_7] .",
